Here are short examples for sending an Escape press to the element with id "modal-close" in common environments. If your modal listens on document/window instead of that element, send the event there (I include that fallback where relevant).

1) Plain browser JavaScript (dispatch keyboard events on the element):
const el = document.querySelector('#modal-close');
el && el.dispatchEvent(new KeyboardEvent('keydown', { key: 'Escape', code: 'Escape', keyCode: 27, which: 27, bubbles: true }));
el && el.dispatchEvent(new KeyboardEvent('keyup',   { key: 'Escape', code: 'Escape', keyCode: 27, which: 27, bubbles: true }));

Fallback (send to document):
document.dispatchEvent(new KeyboardEvent('keydown', { key: 'Escape', code: 'Escape', bubbles: true }));

2) jQuery:
$('#modal-close').trigger($.Event('keydown', { key: 'Escape', which: 27, keyCode: 27 }));

3) Puppeteer (Node):
await page.focus('#modal-close');
await page.keyboard.press('Escape');
// OR element handle:
const el = await page.$('#modal-close');
await el?.press('Escape');

4) Playwright (Node):
await page.press('#modal-close', 'Escape');
// Playwright (Python):
await page.press('#modal-close', 'Escape')

5) Selenium (Python):
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys
el = driver.find_element(By.CSS_SELECTOR, '#modal-close')
el.send_keys(Keys.ESCAPE)

6) Selenium (JavaScript / WebDriverJS):
const el = await driver.findElement(By.css('#modal-close'));
await el.sendKeys(Key.ESCAPE);

Note: Some apps only react to keydown on document/body rather than an element. If pressing the element doesn’t close the modal, send Keys.ESCAPE / keyboard event to the page/document instead. Want the exact snippet for one of these environments? Which one are you using?
